data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_048eecb491317bd80069c20d1ba6808190a57362deef69b9a7","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":95,"text":"You’re in/near **Centralia, Pennsylvania**, which is special because it’s a **modern near–ghost town** created by an **underground coal-seam fire that has been burning beneath the town since 1962**. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))\n\nWhat makes it distinctive:\n\n- **An ongoing underground mine fire (since 1962):** The fire spread through old mine workings under the borough and has been extremely difficult to extinguish. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- **Mass evacuation + condemned town:** Pennsylvania used **eminent domain** to buy out/condemn properties (notably in the early 1990s), and most buildings were demolished, leaving streets/sidewalks with few or no homes. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- **Tiny remaining population:** Centralia’s population fell from hundreds/thousands to just **a handful of residents** (Wikipedia lists **5 residents in 2020**), making it one of the least-populated municipalities in Pennsylvania. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- **Visible environmental aftermath:** Some areas historically had venting smoke/steam and ground hazards (sinkholes, hot ground), which is a big part of its “toxic ghost town” reputation. ([uncoveringpa.com](https://uncoveringpa.com/visiting-centralia))  \n- **“Dark tourism” / pop-culture notoriety:** It became a widely known eerie destination (often linked in travel media to “Silent Hill”-type vibes), though specific claims vary by source. ([greenmatters.com](https://www.greenmatters.com/travel/can-you-visit-centralia-pa))"}

